properties.name: Hakarlavogur
properties.description: Hot Spring is situated on private property. Bathing is only allowed with the owner's permission. Hákarlavogur geothermal pool, despite its secluded location, has gained widespread recognition as one of Iceland's most famous hot pools. Its claim to fame stems from a memorable photo shoot featuring Jason Momoa, renowned for his role as Khal Drogo in the popular TV series Game of Thrones, which took place at this very pool. Finding Hákarlavogur can be quite a challenge. Tucked away among the rocks

properties.description:
Hveragil geothermal area is about 10 km east of the Kverkfjöll mountain hut. over a stretch of around 2 km, hveragil has numerous hot springs measuring 40-60°C, making them ideal for winter bathing. Can only be accessed by 4x4 mountain vehicles or book your tour with a profesional guide.

properties.name: Emstrur
properties.description:
https://nat.is/emstrur-plains/ Emstrur is a desolate grazing area in the southern interior, northwest of the icecap Myrdalsjokull. A few free standing low and steep mountains decorate the area through which the so-called "Laugavegur" hiking trail between Landmannalaugar and Thorsmork lies. In Gully Hattfellsgil is a mountain station of the farmers, who round up the sheep after the summer grazings. .
https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AKcrxGQmqQdLwRxMWEZaghhLOb3cyGqip3EilpuLkv

properties.description: https://goo.gl/maps/2M4SRN46WvMwuo8E8 Jökulgil: A canyon, lying in a demi-circle from Landmannalaugar to the south, into the mountains, for about 30 km. The mountains on it´s east side (Barmur, Hábarmur, Torfajökull and Kaldaklofsjöll), are the clearest signs of the caldera, meant to be at the Torfajökull-area. properties.name: Veiðivötn
properties.description:
https://goo.gl/maps/zfMZZmaE85J7KDeNA This part of the country is among the youngest (1477) and wildest pearls of the central highlands. It includes about 50 lakes of various sizes, many of which are crater lakes. The craters and lakes lie in two rows. Most of the lakes are fed and discharged underground because of the lava fields and porous scoria. This particular spot is on F229 (not shown on Google Maps)

There are showers, toilets, electricity and playground for children. The information center and swimming pool remain open throughout the year and are close at hand. The road is accessible for non-4x4 vehicles although it requires some slow and careful driving in some areas. Lots of beautiful hiking routes are available in the area and on good summer days the weather can be amazing due to it being surrounded by mountains. In

properties.name: Bíldudalur Campsite

properties.name: Flateyri Campsite

Swimming pool, sports hall, shopping and restaurants are all within 5 minutes walking distance from the camp site. The camp site is located right below the avalanche protection wall. properties.name: Melanes campsite
properties.description: https://www.melanes.com Melanes is located at the southernmost part of the Westfjords in Iceland. They have a campsite next to a beautiful beach with a view of the largest known bird cliff in the world, Látrabjarg is a home to millions of birds. In walking distance from the campsite is a seal habitat . Melanes is also a great place for hiking. Open from May 15th until September 15th. Prices: 1.500 kr per night/person 17 years and older Facilities: - WC - Showers (included in the price) - Kitchen

Fisheries have always been important to most of the residents as well as their means of living and survival for many years. The surrounding area of Bolungarvík is quite a popular destination for hikers, horse riding and birdwatching. properties.name: Artun Campsite/Guesthouse

Good facilities and enough space for tents, folding campers, caravans and mobile houses. Good toilet facilities. Toilets with showers, indoor facilities to dine, electricity, waste disposal and possible to get wireless internet connection. Possible to buy wine and beer at Ártún. properties.name: Reykholt Campsite
properties.description: https://tjalda.is/en/reykholt/ The camp site is in the village Reykholt. The camp site is divided into several beautiful groves and one large one. The camp site is a short distance from Gullfoss, waterfall, Geysir, Flúðir and Laugarvatn. It is only about 15 minutes drive to the village Laugarás where the zoo Slakki is. properties.name: Mosskogar Camping

The farm is just off road no 1 on the road to our National Park, Thingvellir and the Golden circle. It has some nice facilities, an outside picnic area and many hiking paths in the surrounding area. properties.description: https://goo.gl/maps/S8WVP6WE5CRvRWe39 A surreal place... It's a kinda of place that is hard to believe that it exists and it's on airbnb! Getting there is not easy though -- river crossing is required! A cabin in the middle of nowhere is quite an understatement for this place we stayed (in summer 2018) in the most remote part of the highlands. No electricity and no running water but we had an amazing time staying at this breathtakingly beautiful part of Iceland and very few venture out here! htt

properties.name: Heiðarbær Campsite
properties.description: https://tjalda.is/en/heidarbaer/ TEMPORARILY CLOSED. The campsite at Heiðarbær is located between the town of Húsavik and Lake Mývatn on road nr 87. The campsite is ideally located for those who want to explore the easternmost part of the Northeast corner of Iceland in a relaxed and beautiful environment. Heidarbær is located only a short distance from many of Iceland’s most popular tourist attractions: Lake Mývatn, Goðafoss waterfall, Ásbyrgi, Jökulsárgljúfur canyon and the river Laxá í Aðaldal

properties.description:
https://nat.is/hut-sigurdarskali-kverkfjoll/ This is a mountain hut cloest to Kverkfjöll which is an impressive hot spring area on top of the glacier. But very difficult to reach, because it requires a few hundered meters steep climbing on the glacier. A hike from the cabin at the foot of the glacier to the spring area and back will take a full day. There are guided tours that start at the cabin.

properties.description: https://www.fi.is/is/skalar/skalar-ferdafelags-islands/thverbrekknamuli MOUNTAIN HUT CAMPSITE This remote campsite is, like all mountain huts, difficult to access and has limited facilities. It is not recommended for campervan travelers. The Thverbrekknamuli hut is situated southeast of Mt Hrutfell, near river Fulakvisl. It is near the middle of the hiking trail on the ancient Kjolur Route. The hut was built in 1980 and accommodates 20 people. The house is heated with gas and an oil-stove. There

properties.name: Kerlingarfjöll campsite & huts
properties.description: https://tjalda.is/en/kerlingarfjoll/ To get to Mountain Kerlingarfjoll you need to drive Kjalveg from the south. Also, if you have 4×4 jeep you can drive to the mountains from Thorsarverum and from Tungvelli in Hrunamannahreppur through Leppistungur. The camping site is located on the banks of the river Asgardsa in the valley Asgardur that is in the northern part of the mountains. The site has showers and a steam bath. The steam bath is located 1km from the camping site. Also there is a playgrou

properties.name: Varmahlíð camping
properties.description: https://maps.google.com/?cid=11162373397123120252 A peaceful and cozy camp site with toilet facilities, hot and cold running water and electricity. There is also a washing machine, tumbel dryer and a shower. A short distance to many activities. There are two football fields next to the camp site and only about 250 meters walk to the swimming pool. The swimming pool is 25 x 12,5 meters with a hot tub and a childrens pool. The childrens pool is a bit warmer with a small waterslider for the smalles

https://goo.gl/maps/XDkX2XxYfmvv4NPV7 The buildings of the farm date from slightly different periods in the 18th- & 19th-centuries. This style of the turf construction was universal in rural areas of Iceland until about 1900, when it was gradually replaced mainly by reinforced concrete, which is typical in most contemporary Icelandic construction today. Extensive turf construction evolved in Iceland owing to the acute shortage of large trees.

Heimaey is home to the world's largest puffin colony, it's towering volcanic cliffs providing the perfect place for the little birds to make their nests. The island is accessed via a ferry or plane.

properties.name: Puffins Hornstrandir Nature Reserve
properties.description:
More at https://epiciceland.net/hornstrandir-guide/ The most remote location in all of Iceland, the uninhabited Hornstrandir was a hideout for bandits and outlaws. Nowadays, it's a beautiful location for hiking in the wilderness and spotting puffins on the cliffs. There are no services here, so you must take all that you need for at least a couple of days with you on your back.
https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AKcrxGTRuHmTapLPASysMnDDcYnQDguRAEwwlYhUn5hX57EsNU0nKRYTaqzJC5Sw

properties.name: Hellnar
properties.description: https://goo.gl/maps/wa82wUDAiXR69Cip7 Hellnar is an old fishing village on the westernmost part of the Snaefellsnes peninsula. It used to be one of the largest fishing stations of the peninsula, the oldest record of seafaring there being from 1560. At the shore are spectacular rock formations. Among them is a protruding cliff called Valasnos. Tunneling into the cliff is a cave renowned for its changing colourful hues, according to the light and sea movement. properties.description: https://goo.gl/maps/sCz33ng7kGxVyy2L8 A beautifully-formed crater rising 60m above the surrounding lava. The spatter cone is the largest crater along a short volcanic rift, 200 m in diameter and 50 m deep. Its last eruption was about 5000-6000 years ago. According to medieval chronics there was also one around the time of the colonisation of Iceland about 1000 years ago, but today it is known that it came from another of the many craters of the valley Hnappadalur which are part of the volcanic s

properties.name: Stórurð Hiking (Mt Dyrfjöll)
properties.description: https://goo.gl/maps/hLXFYcDnaZrnhWHa7 One of East Iceland's most illustrious spots is the Stórurð ("The Giant Boulders"), located to the east of the road leading to Borgarfjörður eystri. Stórurð lies below the small glacier west of Dyrfjöll mountains. It consists of gigantic tuff boulders, charming meadows and attractive ponds. This wonderful scene can be reached in 2.5 hours (one way) on foot from Vatnsskarð pass. To enjoy Dyrfjöll and Stórurð a whole day plan is highly recommended. Trail : htt

The island is a nesting colony for thousands of seabirds, including puffins, guillemots, gannets, kittiwakes, fulmar, shearwaters along with ravens and gyrfalcons. The island is a sheer-sided palagonite rock approximately 180m high and provides a wonderful view over the whole fjord. A trip to Drangey is a unique

New paved road lead to the glacier visitor center and there is a small cafe with wifi here. You can walk to the glacier in minutes. properties.description: https://goo.gl/maps/J81wHCdP5zQtwhpRA Mountains as seen in Rogue One and GoT. Hafursey is an exceptionally beautiful palagonite mountain, situated on the north side of Mýrdalssandur. It is divided by Klofgil Gorge- the west side, Skálafell, is 582m high and Kistufell on the east side, is 513m high. There, the Fulmar has its nesting frounds and the slopes are covered with scrub vegetation, in an area that was once forested. properties.description:

The main reason why the factory was built was because of the growing herring stock coming in to Húnaflói bay. The fishing failed some years after the factory was built and therefore the factory was closed in 1952. The drive here is beautiful but recommended only with 4x4

People from the area and people who have relations to Skálavík have restored some of the houses and new summerhouses have been built. properties.description:
https://goo.gl/maps/2qHvJ8gpG3TmGACu5 Reachable by hiking or mountain biking! Kaldbakur is one of the so-called Westfjords Alps - the tall and pointy mountain range between Dýrafjörður and Arnarfjörður. Most Westfjords mountains are flat topped as a result of Ice Age glaciers, but the "Alps" are tall and pointy and look a little bit like, well, the Alps…Kaldbakur is the tallest of them and, at 998 metres tall, it is the tallest mountain in the Westfjords region.

properties.description: https://goo.gl/maps/XWL5TvNgY6U5v7EJ8 Mýrdalsjökull is a glacier in the south of the Icelandic highlands. It is the country's fourth largest ice cap, covering nearly 600 square kilometres (232 square miles), and its highest peak is almost 1500 meters tall. It is most well-known for sitting atop the notorious and explosive volcano, Katla. properties.name: Reykhólar
properties.description: https://goo.gl/maps/w51pe6tWpNugCZGE6 If you are interested in bird-watching, the small village of Reykhólar is the perfect hub. The sea closest to shore is very shallow and with a high tidal range. These conditions, combined with the marshes and ponds found inland create a bountiful biota and a perfect environment for a rich bird life. properties.description: https://goo.gl/maps/yZWHn9VeERQTbr647 It is no coincidence that Norður Salt is located in Breiðafjörður. Besides being a nature reserve, it is a spectacular land and seascape with shallow waters, small fjords and a myriad of reefs. Already deemed suitable for salt making in 1753, the flow of the pure Arctic seawaters into the bay and the proximity to geothermal hot springs provides the ideal conditions for environmentally sustainable salt making.
